name: Lauramide

For each additional CH2 group in an alkyl chain, the melting point generally increases because of the incremental gain in van der Waals interactions; for lauramide, this can be estimated as +2.5 degrees Celsius per CH2 group. There are 11 carbon atoms in the alkyl chain of lauramide, but since the basic structure's comparison is decanoic acid, we will consider 10 additional CH2 groups. Therefore, the final prediction accounts for the base melting point of decanoic acid (31.6 degrees Celsius), the estimated increase due to the amide group (+50 degrees Celsius), and the contribution of 10 additional CH2 groups (10 * 2.5 degrees Celsius).
